    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey prof, I'm stuck on this one sentence for my syntax assignment. \"The student saw the man with the telescope.\" In my tree diagram, the prepositional phrase \"with the telescope\" is attaching to the Verb Phrase (VP) instead of the Noun Phrase (NP). Can you explain why that attachment happens and what the structural difference looks like?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "This attachment, where \"with the telescope\" modifies the VP, is a classic example of **adjunct modification**, which is often interpreted as a VP-attachment in syntactic trees. It means the phrase describes *how* the action of seeing was performed, rather than describing the man himself. Structurally, the PP is directly sister to the VP, modifying the verb \"saw,\" whereas if it modified the NP, it would be sister to the noun \"man.\"",
      "source": "target",
